            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marco Paolo Reyes was born in Daly City, the youngest child of Filipino immigrants who embodied the promise of the Bay Area. His father, a steadfast postal worker, and his mother, a compassionate registered nurse, instilled in him a profound sense of duty and community. While his older sister pursued a traditional path through college and into finance, Marco was more of a dreamer, drawn to the human stories that pulsed through the city next door.\n\nHe enrolled at San Francisco State University, diving into a Liberal Arts curriculum, fascinated by philosophy and literature. Yet, after two years, he felt adrift. The abstract concepts on the page felt disconnected from the tangible world he wanted to understand. Feeling the pressure to find a stable path, he took the advice of an uncle who had driven a Muni bus for thirty years. He applied for a transit operator position, and to his surprise, found a calling.\n\nThe career change was a pivotal turning point. Learning to navigate a 60-foot articulated bus through the city\u2019s notoriously chaotic streets gave him a concrete purpose his studies had lacked. His bus became a microcosm of San Francisco\u2014a rolling capsule of tourists, commuters, students, and eccentrics. The city wasn\u2019t just a map anymore; it was a living, breathing organism he helped keep alive.\n\nNow 37, Marco lives a steady life in a rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond. His day starts before dawn, his commute a simple ride on the 38R\u2014a line he sometimes drives himself. He\u2019s a beloved regular at a small diner near the bus depot, where he trades stories with other operators. His social life is built around a tight-knit group of childhood friends and his \u201cwork family.\u201d\n\nMarco\u2019s artistic spirit never left him. His iPhone is filled with thousands of photos taken from his driver\u2019s seat: the fog rolling over Sutro Tower, the kaleidoscope of faces reflected in the window, the quiet dawn moments before the city wakes. His dream isn\u2019t wealth, but security\u2014to one day buy a small condo in his neighborhood. He hopes to eventually curate his photos into a small gallery show, a collection he\u2019d call \"Street Level,\" telling the story of the San Francisco he sees, serves, and loves every day."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. He was 20, sitting at the family dinner table in Daly City, the silence deafening after he announced he wasn\u2019t returning to State. His sister, home from her first finance internship, radiated a success he couldn\u2019t grasp. He felt the weight of his parents\u2019 worry, a quiet shame pressing down on him. It wasn\u2019t defiance that stirred in him, but a desperate ache for something real, something tangible. That night, the loud, grinding sound of his uncle\u2019s Muni bus became a comforting thought\u2014a promise of a different kind of purpose.\n\n2. Around age 22, his first solo run on an articulated bus. He remembers gripping the wheel, knuckles white, inching the 60-foot beast through the claustrophobic Stockton Tunnel during rush hour. The roar was deafening, his heart pounding. When he finally emerged into the chaos of Union Square, a wave of pure exhilaration hit him. It was a baptism by fire. In that moment of successful navigation, the abstract search for meaning ended. He wasn\u2019t just driving; he was a part of the city\u2019s pulse.\n\n3. He was 27, driving the 1-California on a misty February morning. An elderly woman, a regular he knew only by her quiet nods, stopped as she was getting off. She pressed a small bag into his hand with a weathered smile, revealing a handful of White Rabbit candies for Lunar New Year. No words were needed. In that moment of simple, cross-cultural gratitude, he understood his job wasn't about routes or schedules. It was about carrying people\u2019s lives, and being trusted with their daily journeys.\n\n4. Stuck in traffic on Masonic around age 30, waiting for the light. The fog had perfectly decapitated Sutro Tower, turning it into a mysterious monolith. Reflected in his giant side-view mirror was the face of a student, headphones on, lost in their own world. He raised his phone and framed it all in one shot. Looking at the image later, it clicked. This wasn't just a snapshot; it was a narrative only he could see. The idea for his \"Street Level\" gallery solidified from a vague dream into a concrete mission.\n\n5. Just last year, his father, retired from the post office, rode his entire 38R shift with him. For hours, his dad sat quietly, watching him navigate the chaos, call out stops, and help an old man with his groceries. At the end of the line, as the bus emptied, his father looked at him with a new understanding. \u201cThis is hard work. You\u2019re steady, son. Like me.\u201d In that simple statement, Marco felt a profound sense of peace. The dreamer had finally earned a different, more meaningful, kind of patriarchal approval."
